    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window. Fielies spoke about her own personal experiences with cyber bullies after she won Idols and appealed to pupils to consider the harmful impact bullying has on its victims. “It started when I won the competition. I received a lot of love and support from people in the beginning, but I also got rude and ugly messages. People judged me on my appearance and how I chose to live my life.” Schäfer said that given the prevalence of bullying in schools, the department had developed the campaign to highlight the effects of bullying on pupils and draw attention to the fact that pupils who filmed, posted or distributed videos were participating in bullying. She added that in order to get the message across, the department had sought the assistance of digital specialists and child psychologists to provide advice on the development of the online campaign. “The campaign first involves the filming of a fake bullying incident in a school yard and ends with the simple message: ‘raise your voice, not your phone.’ “But (eventually) it leads the reader to the realisation that pupils are also participating in bullying by filming the incident rather than intervening to bring an end to the abuse,” added Schäfer. The campaign can be accessed at http://www.wcg-antibullying.co.za/ @IAmAthinaMay  athina.may@inl.co.za  Cape Argus